---
title: "A Formal Specification of the NullSec LoRa Mesh Protocol"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-05
abstract: This document provides a formal specification of the NullSec LoRa mesh protocol implemented in Lateralus. It covers packet grammar in EBNF, state machine transitions, security properties, and performance model.
---

# Introduction

The NullSec LoRa mesh protocol is an open-source implementation of the LoRaWAN protocol for low-power wide-area networks. Our goal with this project is to provide a formal specification that accurately captures the protocol's behavior.

## Section 1: Packet Grammar

We define the packet structure as follows:

packet::=header|payload

header::=source_address|destination_address|sequence_number|priority|data_rate

payload::=application_data

// EBNF grammar
packet ::= header | payload
header ::= source_address | destination_address | sequence_number | priority | data_rate
payload ::= application_data

## Section 2: State Machine Transitions

We use the finite-state machine (FSM) approach to describe the protocol's behavior. The FSM has four states: IDLE, SENT, RECV, and ACK.

// Define the states
const States = ['IDLE', 'SENT', 'RECV', 'ACK']

// Transition function
fn transition(current_state: States, event: string): States {
    match current_state {
        'IDLE' => {
            if event == 'PACKET_SENT' {
                return 'SENT'
            } else {
                return 'IDLE'
            }
        }
        'SENT' => {
            if event == 'RECEIVED' {
                return 'RECV'
            } else {
                return 'SENT'
            }
        }
        'RECV' => {
            if event == 'ACKNOWLEDGED' {
                return 'ACK'
            } else {
                return 'RECV'
            }
        }
        'ACK' => {
            return 'IDLE'
        }
    }
}

## Section 3: Security Properties

We prove that the protocol satisfies the following security properties:

* Confidentiality: The application data is encrypted with AES-256.
